DAY 7: CONDITIONAL STATEMENTS
EXPLANATION:
  Conditionals let your code make decisions and follow different paths based on conditions.
  
  IF STATEMENT (execute if condition true):
    if (condition) {
      // code runs only if condition is true
    }
    Example:
      let age = 20;
      if (age >= 18) {
        console.log("You are an adult");
      }
  
  IF-ELSE STATEMENT (two paths):
    if (condition) {
      // runs if true
    } else {
      // runs if false
    }
    Example:
      if (age >= 18) {
        console.log("Adult");
      } else {
        console.log("Minor");
      }
  
  IF-ELSE-IF-ELSE STATEMENT (multiple paths):
    if (condition1) {
      // runs if condition1 true
    } else if (condition2) {
      // runs if condition2 true (and condition1 false)
    } else if (condition3) {
      // runs if condition3 true (and previous false)
    } else {
      // runs if all conditions false
    }
    Example:
      if (score >= 90) {
        console.log("A");
      } else if (score >= 80) {
        console.log("B");
      } else if (score >= 70) {
        console.log("C");
      } else {
        console.log("F");
      }
  
  SWITCH STATEMENT (check single value against multiple cases):
    switch (value) {
      case value1:
        // code if matches value1
        break; // MUST exit or will continue to next case
      case value2:
        // code if matches value2
        break;
      default:
        // code if no match (like else)
    }
    Example:
      let day = 1;
      switch (day) {
        case 1:
          console.log("Monday");
          break;
        case 2:
          console.log("Tuesday");
          break;
        default:
          console.log("Invalid day");
      }
  
  COMMON MISTAKES:
  - Forgetting 'break;' in switch (falls through to next case)
  - Using = instead of == or === in condition
  - Not understanding 'else if' is one path (not independent if)

