DAY 8: LOOPS
EXPLANATION:
  Loops let you repeat code multiple times. Essential for processing collections of data.
  
  FOR LOOP (most common, when you know how many iterations):
    for (initialize; condition; increment) {
      // code repeats while condition true
    }
    Example:
      for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        console.log(i); // outputs: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
      }
    How it works:
      1. Initialize: let i = 0 (runs once)
      2. Check condition: i < 5? (if false, stop)
      3. Execute body
      4. Execute increment: i++
      5. Back to step 2
  
  WHILE LOOP (when condition unknown, repeat while condition true):
    while (condition) {
      // code repeats
      // MUST change something to avoid infinite loop
    }
    Example:
      let i = 0;
      while (i < 5) {
        console.log(i);
        i++; // must increment or infinite loop!
      }
  
  DO-WHILE LOOP (execute at least once, then check condition):
    do {
      // code runs at least once
    } while (condition);
    Example:
      let i = 0;
      do {
        console.log(i);
        i++;
      } while (i < 5);
      // This will always run at least once
  
  LOOP CONTROL:
    break;    // exits loop immediately
    continue; // skips to next iteration
    
    Example with break:
      for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        if (i === 5) break; // exits loop when i = 5
        console.log(i); // outputs: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
      }
    
    Example with continue:
      for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        if (i === 2) continue; // skips i = 2
        console.log(i); // outputs: 0, 1, 3, 4
      }
  
  COMMON MISTAKES:
  - Infinite loops (condition never becomes false)
  - Off-by-one errors (i < 5 vs i <= 5)
  - Forgetting to increment in while loop
  - Using break/continue incorrectly

