DAY 9: ARRAYS
EXPLANATION:
  Arrays are ordered collections of values. They're fundamental to programming.
  
  CREATING ARRAYS:
    let arr = [];              // empty array
    let arr = [1, 2, 3];       // with initial values
    let arr = new Array();     // less common
    
    Arrays can hold any mix of types:
    let mixed = [1, "hello", true, null, undefined];
  
  ACCESSING ELEMENTS:
    let arr = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"];
    arr[0];  // "apple"
    arr[1];  // "banana"
    arr[2];  // "cherry"
    arr[3];  // undefined (doesn't exist)
    
    IMPORTANT: Indexing starts at 0, not 1
  
  ARRAY PROPERTIES:
    arr.length;  // number of elements
    
    Example:
      let arr = [1, 2, 3];
      console.log(arr.length); // 3
  
  MODIFYING ARRAYS:
    arr[0] = 5;  // change first element
    arr.push(4); // add to end
    arr.pop();   // remove from end
    arr.shift(); // remove from beginning
    arr.unshift(0); // add to beginning
  
  ARRAY METHODS (very important):
    .push(value)    - adds element to end, returns new length
    .pop()          - removes last element, returns it
    .shift()        - removes first element, returns it
    .unshift(value) - adds to beginning, returns new length
    .indexOf(value) - finds position of value, returns index or -1
    .includes(value) - checks if value exists, returns true/false
    .slice(start, end) - creates copy from start to end (not inclusive)
    .splice(index, deleteCount, item1, item2...) - modifies array
    
  ARRAY METHODS FOR TRANSFORMATION (very important):
    .map(function)    - transforms each element
    .filter(function) - keeps elements where function returns true
    .reduce(function) - combines elements into single value
    .forEach(function) - runs function for each element
    
    Example of map:
      let numbers = [1, 2, 3];
      let doubled = numbers.map(x => x * 2);
      // doubled = [2, 4, 6]
    
    Example of filter:
      let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
      let evens = numbers.filter(x => x % 2 === 0);
      // evens = [2, 4]
  
  ITERATING ARRAYS:
    // Traditional for loop
    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
      console.log(arr[i]);
    }
    
    // forEach method
    arr.forEach(element => {
      console.log(element);
    });
    
    // for...of loop (modern)
    for (let element of arr) {
      console.log(element);
    }

