DAY 14.1: HOISTING (CRITICAL DEEP DIVE)
EXPLANATION:
  Hoisting is how JavaScript moves declarations to the top before execution.
  
  VARIABLE HOISTING WITH VAR:
    console.log(x); // outputs: undefined (not error!)
    var x = 5;
    console.log(x); // outputs: 5
    
    What really happens:
    var x;           // declaration hoisted (value = undefined)
    console.log(x);  // undefined
    x = 5;           // assignment happens here
    console.log(x);  // 5
  
  VARIABLE HOISTING WITH LET/CONST:
    console.log(x); // ReferenceError!
    let x = 5;
    
    This is because of Temporal Dead Zone:
    - Space between start of block and line where let is declared
    - Accessing variable in TDZ causes ReferenceError
  
  FUNCTION HOISTING:
    console.log(add(3, 4)); // works! outputs: 7
    
    function add(a, b) {
      return a + b;
    }
    
    Entire function is hoisted and callable before declaration.
    But function expressions are NOT hoisted:
    console.log(add(3, 4)); // ERROR
    
    const add = (a, b) => a + b;
  
  WHY THIS MATTERS:
    - Hoisting can lead to unexpected behavior
    - Using var before declaration gives undefined (confusing!)
    - let/const prevent this with strict error
    - Always declare variables before using them

