DAY 16: CALLBACK FUNCTIONS
EXPLANATION:
  A callback is a function passed as argument to another function, to be called later.
  
  BASIC CALLBACK:
    function greet(name, callback) {
      console.log("Hello, " + name);
      callback(); // execute the callback
    }
    
    function sayGoodbye() {
      console.log("Goodbye!");
    }
    
    greet("John", sayGoodbye);
    // outputs:
    // Hello, John
    // Goodbye!
  
  CALLBACKS WITH PARAMETERS:
    function calculate(a, b, operation) {
      return operation(a, b);
    }
    
    calculate(5, 3, (x, y) => x + y);     // 8
    calculate(5, 3, (x, y) => x - y);     // 2
    calculate(5, 3, (x, y) => x * y);     // 15
  
  ARRAY METHOD CALLBACKS:
    [1, 2, 3].forEach(num => console.log(num));
    
    [1, 2, 3, 4].filter(num => num > 2); // [3, 4]
    
    [1, 2, 3].map(num => num * 2);       // [2, 4, 6]
  
  ASYNCHRONOUS CALLBACKS:
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("After 1 second");
    }, 1000);
    
    This runs the callback after 1000 milliseconds.
  
  CALLBACK HELL (problem with nested callbacks):
    getData(function(data) {
      processData(data, function(result) {
        saveResult(result, function(status) {
          console.log("Saved: " + status);
        });
      });
    });
    
    This is hard to read. Solutions:
    - Use arrow functions for cleaner syntax
    - Use Promises (Days 24-25)
    - Use async/await

