DAY 22: JS ENGINE (INTERNALS)
EXPLANATION:
  How does JavaScript code actually execute? What happens in the engine?
  
  THREE PHASES:
    
    1. PARSING PHASE
       - Engine reads source code
       - Converts to Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)
       - Checks for syntax errors
    
    2. COMPILATION PHASE
       - Creates Execution Context
       - Sets up memory for variables
       - Hoisting occurs here
       - Prepares bytecode
    
    3. EXECUTION PHASE
       - Code actually runs
       - Values assigned to variables
       - Functions called, callbacks queued
  
  EXECUTION CONTEXT:
    When code runs, an Execution Context is created. It contains:
    - Variable Environment (variables declared here)
    - Lexical Environment (access to outer scope)
    - this binding
    
    Example:
      let globalVar = "global";
      
      function test() {
        let localVar = "local";  // in function's execution context
        console.log(localVar);   // accessible
      }
      
      test(); // creates new execution context for test()
  
  CALL STACK:
    Stack of execution contexts. Last-in, first-out (LIFO).
    
    function a() {
      console.log("a");
      b();
      console.log("back to a");
    }
    
    function b() {
      console.log("b");
      c();
      console.log("back to b");
    }
    
    function c() {
      console.log("c");
    }
    
    a();
    
    Call Stack evolution:
    [Global]
    [Global, a]
    [Global, a, b]
    [Global, a, b, c]
    [Global, a, b]
    [Global, a]
    [Global]
    
    Output:
    a
    b
    c
    back to b
    back to a
  
  OPTIMIZATION:
    Modern engines optimize code:
    - JIT Compilation (Just-In-Time)
    - Inline caching
    - Hidden classes
    - Garbage collection
    
    This is why JavaScript is fast!

