DAY 24: PROMISES (ASYNC FOUNDATION)
EXPLANATION:
  Promises handle asynchronous operations. They represent a value that may not be ready yet.
  
  PROMISE STATES:
    A Promise is in one of three states:
    1. PENDING - operation hasn't finished yet
    2. FULFILLED - operation succeeded, has a value
    3. REJECTED - operation failed, has an error
    
    Once settled (fulfilled or rejected), state cannot change.
  
  CREATING PROMISES:
    const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      // do something async
      if (/* success */) {
        resolve(value);   // fulfill with value
      } else {
        reject(error);    // reject with error
      }
    });
  
  CONSUMING PROMISES:
    promise
      .then(result => {
        // runs if promise fulfilled
        console.log(result);
      })
      .catch(error => {
        // runs if promise rejected
        console.log(error);
      })
      .finally(() => {
        // runs always, for cleanup
      });
  
  PRACTICAL EXAMPLE:
    function fetchUserData(userId) {
      return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        setTimeout(() => {
          if (userId > 0) {
            resolve({id: userId, name: "John"});
          } else {
            reject(new Error("Invalid user ID"));
          }
        }, 1000);
      });
    }
    
    fetchUserData(1)
      .then(user => console.log("User:", user))
      .catch(error => console.log("Error:", error));
  
  PROMISE HELPERS:
    Promise.all([promise1, promise2])
      - Waits for all promises to fulfill
      - If any rejects, entire thing rejects
    
    Promise.race([promise1, promise2])
      - Returns result of first settled promise
    
    Promise.resolve(value)
      - Creates fulfilled promise with value
    
    Promise.reject(error)
      - Creates rejected promise with error

